\begin{align*}
\text{A)}\ & x=9 &
\text{B)}\ & x=\frac{5}{6} \\
\text{C)}\ & x=\frac{23}{6} &
\text{D)}\ & x=\frac{7}{3} \\
\end{align*}    
\end{problem}
\noindent

gpt-4-0125-preview_response:
To solve the equation $-2(3 x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}}=-54$, we will first isolate the expression with the exponent $\frac{3}{2}$:

\begin{align*}
-2(3 x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}} &=-54 \\
(3 x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}} &= \frac{-54}{-2} \\
(3 x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}} &= 27
\end{align*}

Next, we eliminate the exponent $\frac{3}{2}$. Knowing that raising both sides of the equation to the power of $\frac{2}{3}$ is the inverse operation, we get:

\begin{align*}
\left((3 x+2)^{\frac{3}{2}}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}} &= 27^{\frac{2}{3}} \\
3 x + 2 &= 3^3^{\frac{2}{3}} \\
3 x + 2 &= 3^2 \\
3x + 2 &= 9
\end{align*}

Isolating $x$ gives:

\begin{align*}
3x &= 9 - 2 \\
3x &= 7 \\
x &= \frac{7}{3}
\end{align*}

Hence, the solution is:

### Answer: D) \(x = \frac{7}{3}\)

